  "in_reply_to": "2026-04-30-1100--memodef-strategist--memodef-strategist--session-handoff-post-orgdef-bootstrap.openthing",
  "body": "## Acknowledgment — handoff received cleanly\n\nThe desktop arc closed the receive-side of the previous session-handoff memo with two visible moves:\n\n- **Maildir scaffold established** (commit `89dd790`, 2026-04-30 09:15 EDT) — `memos/inbox/`, `memos/read/`, `memos/archive/` each with `.gitkeep`. Goes beyond what the previous handoff memo requested; landed the full RECOMMENDED convention proactively rather than waiting for first-use creation. Defensible — establishes the structure as the canonical state of the repo, making the convention discoverable to future readers without depending on convention-aware first-touchers.\n- **Session-handoff memo marked read** (commit `b290b48`, 2026-04-30 09:20 EDT) — `git mv memos/inbox/...session-handoff... memos/read/`. Literally followed the \"How to mark this read\" instructions at the bottom of the previous memo. The substrate exercised itself end-to-end.\n\n## Validation arc closed\n\nThe orgdef-strategist peer review of the memodef-spec orgdef derivation arrived (now at `memos/read/2026-04-30-1100--orgdef-strategist--memodef-strategist--derivation-review-passes.openthing` after receiver-side processing):\n\n- **Verdict: PASS.** No artifact-level changes requested for `memodef-spec-org/orgdef.openthing`.\n- **Five template-patch findings queued** in orgdef-spec — directly traceable to the structured complaints in the canonical-derivation-experience memo. The experience-memo channel had its intended effect; structured complaints produced template patches.\n- **One disagreement worth tracking:** orgdef-strategist declined the proposed SLOT-FILL category between REPLACE and INHERIT/REFINE on the inheritance conventions table, preferring a one-sentence note in the existing table instead. They are open to reconsidering if catdef/roledef derivations replicate the friction. Watch the next derivations for evidence either way before re-pressing the case.\n\n## Three workflow questions surfaced — none urgent, all worth carrying forward\n\n### 1. Where do incoming memos land — flat `memos/` or `memos/inbox/`?\n\nThe orgdef-strategist review memo arrived at the flat `memos/` level (sender chose flat, matching the pre-convention catdef-strategist peer memo's location), not `memos/inbox/`. The Inbox lifecycle convention is RECOMMENDED (not REQUIRED) per [memodef-spec README.md](../../README.md#inbox-lifecycle-recommended), so flat is permitted. But it raises a real question:\n\n- **Sender-places-at-inbox/:** sender knows the recipient's convention and writes directly to `memos/inbox/`. Cleanest for the receiver, but requires senders to discover recipient conventions.\n- **Receiver-moves-on-receipt:** sender places anywhere reasonable; receiver `git mv`'s into `memos/inbox/` as part of mailbox-checking, then to `memos/read/` on processing. Receiver bears the convention overhead.\n- **Pragmatic mixed:** flat is fine; lifecycle-tracking is opt-in for adopters who want it.\n\nI lean **sender-places-at-inbox-when-the-recipient-org-adopts-the-convention**. Discoverability proposal: extend the orgdef `x.org.memo_location` extension shape (or add a sibling `x.org.memo_inbox` field) to declare the inbox path explicitly — `\"memos/inbox/\"` if maildir adopted, `\"memos/\"` if flat. Senders read this when composing memos and target accordingly. Scope: an orgdef-strategist proposal, not memodef.\n\nFor this current case: I moved the orgdef-strategist memo to `memos/read/` directly on processing, skipping the intermediate `memos/inbox/` step since I was the receiver-and-processor in the same action. Defensible as a per-action shortcut.\n\n### 2. Who commits an incoming memo — sender or receiver?\n\nThe orgdef-strategist review memo arrived in the laptop working tree but was untracked. The current session committed it under memodef-strategist authorship as receipt-of-record. Open question:\n\n- **Sender commits + pushes:** memo lives in version control before the receiver opens it; receiver doesn't need to commit. Cleaner; matches \"publishing\" semantics; sender-of-record is the commit author.\n- **Receiver commits on receipt:** memo enters version control as part of the receive action; sender pushes to a working branch (or hands the file off some other way) and the receiver \"merges\" via commit. Couples memos to receive-action timing; receiver-of-record authors the commit.\n\nThe catdef-strategist architecture-validation peer memo (2026-04-29) was also receiver-committed (Director did the commit; not the sender). So receiver-commits is the de-facto pattern in catdef-family memos so far. This session continues the pattern. Worth canonizing or revisiting deliberately — the sender-commits pattern would require senders to have push access to recipients' repos, which is already true under the catdef-org authorization-implies-write-access discipline; so the choice is workflow preference, not access constraint.\n\n### 3. Form choice — typed `memodef:Memo` vs legacy `x.memo.*`\n\nThe orgdef-strategist review memo uses legacy `x.memo.*` form. The previous session-handoff memo and this memo use typed `memodef:Memo` form. Both are valid per [SCHEMA migration path](../../SCHEMA.md#backward-compatible-legacy-form-xmemo-extensions-on-a-generic-catdef-thing). memodef-spec/memos/ is now mixing forms:\n\n| Memo | Form |\n|---|---|\n| 2026-04-29-1700 catdef-strategist architecture-validation | typed |\n| 2026-04-30-1100 orgdef-strategist derivation-review | legacy |\n| 2026-04-30-1100 memodef-strategist session-handoff | typed |\n| 2026-04-30-1230 memodef-strategist workflow-observations (this) | typed |\n\nSibling-spec memos in `orgdef/memos/` and `roledef/memos/` are uniformly legacy. The orgdef-strategist explicitly parked the typed-vs-legacy tension in their review.\n\nNot urgent. Editorial migration of legacy memos to typed form is a memodef-maintainer-scope cleanup when someone has spare cycles, and only for memos in this repo. Cross-family migration is not memodef's call.\n\n## What I missed in the previous session-handoff memo\n\nThe previous handoff memo would have been more useful had it included:\n\n- An explicit \"**incoming memos may arrive at any folder; the convention applies to outgoing-from-this-repo and to lifecycle-tracking-after-receipt**\" note. The desktop arc inferred this correctly but had to discover it.\n- A \"**pending review**\" item: the experience memo to orgdef-strategist (sent 2026-04-30 1000) was awaiting their reply, which has now arrived as the derivation-review-passes memo. The next session arrives with that loop already closed; future handoff memos should explicitly list outstanding peer-review threads.\n- A \"**things to watch for in the inbox**\" section anticipating expected-arrival memos. Trade-off: this risks the handoff memo growing a \"future state\" section that drifts; keep it minimal if added.\n\n## Action items (none urgent)\n\n- The orgdef-strategist review memo needs no reply (action_required: false on their side).\n- The five template-patch findings will land as orgdef-spec proposals; nothing required from this seat.\n- Watch catdef-spec and roledef-spec orgdef derivations (when they happen, Director-driven) for evidence about the SLOT-FILL category disagreement.\n- Carry the three workflow questions above into future strategist sessions; we have one data point per question, which is enough to surface but not enough to canonize.\n\n— memodef-strategist (laptop arc continued, 2026-04-30, post-desktop-arc-review)\n",
  "action_required": false,
